		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Truss</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Truss_(disambiguation)" title="Truss (disambiguation)">Truss (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:352px;"><a href="/wiki/File:80ft_Double_Chorded_Heavy_Timber_Truss.JPG" class="image" title="Double chorded heavy timber truss with 80ft clear span."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/80ft_Double_Chorded_Heavy_Timber_Truss.JPG/350px-80ft_Double_Chorded_Heavy_Timber_Truss.JPG" width="350" height="263" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:80ft_Double_Chorded_Heavy_Timber_Truss.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Double chorded heavy timber truss with 80ft clear span.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:352px;"><a href="/wiki/File:RRTrussBridgeSideView.jpg" class="image" title="Truss bridge for a single track railway, converted to pedestrian use and pipeline support"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/RRTrussBridgeSideView.jpg/350px-RRTrussBridgeSideView.jpg" width="350" height="175" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:RRTrussBridgeSideView.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Truss_bridge" title="Truss bridge">Truss bridge</a> for a single track railway, converted to pedestrian use and pipeline support</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Architecture" title="Architecture">architecture</a> and <a href="/wiki/Structural_engineering" title="Structural engineering">structural engineering</a>, a <b>truss</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Architectural_structure" title="Architectural structure">structure</a> comprising one or more triangular units constructed with straight slender members whose ends are connected at joints referred to as <a href="/wiki/Vertex_(geometry)" title="Vertex (geometry)">nodes</a>. External forces and reactions to those forces are considered to act only at the nodes and result in forces in the members which are either <a href="/wiki/Tension" title="Tension">tensile</a> or <a href="/wiki/Compression" title="Compression">compressive</a> forces. Moments (torsional forces) are explicitly excluded because, and only because, all the joints in a truss are treated as <a href="/w/index.php?title=Revolute&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Revolute (page does not exist)">revolutes</a>.</p>
<p>A planar truss is one where all the members and nodes lie within a two dimensional plane, while a space truss has members and nodes extending into three dimensions.</p>
